Fungus Cryptococcus gatti Threat to Healthy People
' Fungus Cryptococcus gatti Threat to Healthy People \n An airborne fungus called Cryptococcus gattii \nis making its way down from British Columbia to the coastal northwestern United States, and it appears to have a lethal agenda. C. gattii, which usually only infects individuals whose immune systems are compromised, is now attacking healthy people, and it has affected some animals as well. \nThe report on this potentially deadly strain of fungus appeared in the online journal PLoS Pathogens  ', 'British Columbia Province, Canada | Cryptococcosis | Humans', 'United States | Cryptococcosis | Humans'

441858

HM Community News Reports
22 Apr 2010
Rift Valley Fever
South Africa
'-28.998529','25.092541',5,179
Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries update on Rift Valley fever
' Rift Valley fever report \n22 April 2010\n The Department of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries remains concerned about the spread of Rift Valley fever (RVF) and the rising of human cases reported. Our team continues to work with the affected provinces, experts from the Onderstepoort Veterinary Institute and the Onderstepoort Biological Products (OBP) (Ltd) vaccine facility to bring this outbreak under control. OBP will prioritise the distribution of vaccines to the affected provinces.\n Rift Valley fever is a viral disease of animals that is spread by mosquitoes, causing abortions in sheep, goats and cattle and can cause death in young animals. Humans can get infected if they come into contact with blood and other body fluids from infected animals, or if they assist with abortions and handle infective aborted material, like foetuses, placentas and placental fluids. It is not for the first time that South Africa experiences the disease. The current outbreak was triggered by the high rainfall experienced at the beginning of the year in the Free State province.\n A total of 183 outbreaks have been reported until 21 April 2010, with more than 6 000 animal cases and more than 3 500 animal deaths. Sheep are by far the most affected species, with some cattle and goats also affected. A small number of wildlife has also been affected. The Free State province is the worst hit by the disease, followed by the Northern Cape and the Eastern Cape provinces. A few outbreaks have been reported in the North West, Western Cape, Gauteng and Mpumalanga provinces. ', 'South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Livestock (domestic)'
http://www.info.gov.za/speeches/2010/10042216251001.htm
Livestock (domestic)

HM Community News Reports
20 Apr 2010
Rift Valley Fever
South Africa
'-28.998529','25.092541',5,179
Health on Rift Valley fever (RVF) during 2010 FIFA World Cup
u'[ Speeches & statements ]\n Rift Valley fever (RVF) not a risk to World Cup \n The National Institute of Communicable Disease (NICD) Laboratory has confirmed this afternoon that visitors coming to South Africa for the 2010 FIFA World Cup are not at risk of Rift Valley Fever (RVF).\n \xe2\x80\x9cVisitors coming to South Africa for the FIFA World Cup are not at risk unless they handle infected carcasses on farms or handle raw meat from infected animals. It is highly unlikely that visitors would be involved in these activities. The formal meat supply is well controlled and affected animals are excluded from the food chain in abattoirs. There is no risk to visitors to game parks as the disease typically only affects ruminants such as sheep, cattle and goats. South Africa is looking forward to extending a warm welcome to the country for the 2010 FIFA World Cup, and to reassure visitors that everything will be done to ensure their safety and health,\xe2\x80\x9d said Dr Lucille Blumberg from NICD.\n This follows an earlier media alert by the Department of Health to reassure the public that the Department of Health and Department of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries, supported by the South African Field Epidemiology and Training Programme (SA-FELTP) and National Institute of Communicable Diseases (NICD), observed by a technical expert from the World Health Organisation Geneva, are working round-the-clock to contain the spread of the Rift Valley fever (RVF). ', 'South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans'
http://www.info.gov.za/speeches/2010/10042016051003.htm

Health update on Rift Valley fever
'[ Speeches & statements ]\n Nine deaths from Rift Valley fever \n11 April 2010\n A total of 111 laboratory confirmed human cases of Rift Valley fever (RVF) have been reported by the National Institute of Communicable Disease (NICD) laboratory. Nine people have died since the first incident on 13 February 2010.\n Of the 111 cases, 81 cases and five deaths are from Free State, seven from the Eastern Cape, and 22 cases and four deaths are from Northern Cape and one from North West. HM Community News Reports
29 Apr 2010
Rift Valley Fever
Little Karoo, Western Cape, South Africa
'-33.750000','21.000000',5,12168
Rift Valley Fever - first human death in Western Cape
u' The National Institute for Communicable Diseases (NICD) confirmed today that a 49-year old male from the Karoo has been the first human to die from Rift Valley Fever in the Western Cape. He died in Oudtshoorn Hospital. The NICD is still investigating the patient\xe2\x80\x99s source of exposure. It is unsure in which manner he contracted the disease. There have been confirmed cases of Rift Valley Fever in animals in the Oudtshoorn area.\n\nThe Western Cape Department of Agriculture also confirmed today that two alpaca\xe2\x80\x99s have died from Rift Valley Fever on a farm in Simondium, outside Paarl in the Western Cape. This is the latest confirmed case of Rift Valley Fever in animals in the Province, and also the first case in the south western part of the Western Cape Province. Visit www.oie.int for more information on the spread of the disease in animals. ', 'Little Karoo, Western Cape, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'Western Cape Province, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Alpaca'
http://www.health-e.org.za/news/article.php?uid=20032762

HM Community News Reports
28 Apr 2010
Rift Valley Fever
Little Karoo, Western Cape, South Africa
'-33.750000','21.000000',5,12168
Eyewitness News: Department appeals for calm
' The Western Cape Health Department has appealed for calm following the confirmation of the first Rift Valley Fever fatality in the province. A farm worker in the Little Karoo contracted the disease after being exposed to infected livestock. While initial tests proved negative, these results were invalidated by a second batch of post-mortem tests. Health officials moved to allay fears and said the death should not spark unnecessary panic. So far, the majority of infections in humans have been reported in the Northern Cape \n death was an isolated case. Botha said his department as working closely with agriculture officials to curb the spread of the disease. (Edited by Danya Philander) \n How were you involved or affected? * \n Traffic officials brace for busy day \n New Media company chastised for sexist mockup  ', 'Little Karoo, Western Cape, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans'
http://www.eyewitnessnews.co.za/articleprog.aspx?id=38297

'-29.000000','26.000000',5,3588
RVF spreads to Western Cape
' RVF spreads to Western Cape \nIssued by National Ministry of Health \n28 April 2010 \nFive additional human cases of Rift Valley fever (RVF) - 4 from Northern Cape and 1 from Western Cape - have been confirmed by the South African National Institute of Communicable Disease (NICD) Laboratory. \nThe total number of human cases of RVF now stands at 160. Of these, 103 from Free State, 45 from Northern Cape, 8 from Eastern Cape, 1 from North West, 1 from Western Cape and 2 additional cases whose history is still unknown. A total of 13 mortalities have also been reported - 7 from Free State and 5 from the Northern Cape and 1 from Western Cape - a 41-year-old male.  ', 'Free State, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'Western Cape Province, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'Eastern Cape Province, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'Northern Cape Region, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'North-West Region, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans'

Of these, 103 from Free State, 45 from Northern Cape, 8 from Eastern Cape, 1 from North West, 1 from Western Cape and 2 additional cases whose history is still unknown. '38.528179','71.042000',5,141
Poliomyelitis: the situation in Tajikistan
u' Sur les 32 cas confirm\xe9s d\u2019infection par le poliovirus sauvage, 17 ont moins de deux ans, 14 entre deux et cinq ans et le dernier a entre 6 et 15 ans. Il s\u2019agit de gar\xe7ons pour 66 % des cas. Jusqu\u2019\xe0 pr\xe9sent, la paralysie est apparue en mars pour 15 cas confirm\xe9s et en avril pour les 17 autres cas. On a des informations sur les ant\xe9c\xe9dents vaccinaux de 21 des 32 cas confirm\xe9s. Il a \xe9t\xe9 signal\xe9 que 2 d\u2019entre eux (10 %) avaient re\xe7u moins de trois doses de VPO et 19 (90 %) trois doses ou plus.  Tous les cas ont \xe9t\xe9 signal\xe9s dans le Sud-ouest du pays, y compris dans la capitale, Douchanb\xe9. Cette r\xe9gion se trouve \xe0 la fronti\xe8re de l\u2019Afghanistan et de l\u2019Ouzb\xe9kistan. Par s\xe9quen\xe7age, on a d\xe9sormais d\xe9termin\xe9 que la parent\xe9 g\xe9n\xe9tique \xe9tait la plus grande avec un virus de l\u2019Uttar Pradesh (Inde). Face \xe0 cette flamb\xe9e, le gouvernement du Tadjikistan a confirm\xe9 la planification de trois tourn\xe9es suppl\xe9mentaires de vaccination ciblant tous les enfants de moins de 5 ans (soit environ 1,1 million d\u2019enfants). Le vaccin antipoliomy\xe9litique buccal monovalent de type 1 sera utilis\xe9 pour obtenir rapidement l\u2019immunit\xe9 des enfants dans le pays. La premi\xe8re campagne commencera dans la capitale, Douchanb\xe9, et dans six districts voisins le 1er mai. Les autres r\xe9gions commenceront la vaccination des enfants de moins de 5 ans le 4 mai. Deux tourn\xe9es nationales suppl\xe9mentaires sont pour l\u2019instant pr\xe9vues du 18 au 22 mai et du 1er au 5 juin.  Les pays voisins r\xe9agissent \xe0 cette flamb\xe9e en renfor\xe7ant la surveillance dans tous les \xe9tablissements de sant\xe9 et sites de notification, tout en examinant le statut vaccinal des enfants. L\u2019Ouzb\xe9kistan (avec une population cibl\xe9e de 2,89 millions d\u2019enfants de moins de 5 ans) planifie deux tourn\xe9es nationales de vaccination suppl\xe9mentaires, en s\u2019effor\xe7ant de les synchroniser avec le Tadjikistan en mai et en juin. Le Kirghizistan ach\xe8ve demain une campagne, que les autorit\xe9s avaient planifi\xe9e dans le cadre de la Semaine europ\xe9enne de la vaccination, pour renforcer l\u2019immunit\xe9 des enfants contre les maladies \xe0 pr\xe9vention vaccinale, dont la poliomy\xe9lite. Ce pays pr\xe9voie d\u2019organiser des journ\xe9es locales de vaccination suppl\xe9mentaires dans certaines zones g\xe9ographiques bien d\xe9finies.  ', 'Tajikistan | Polio | Humans'
http://www.who.int/entity/csr/don/2010_04_29/fr/index.html

'38.528179','71.042000',5,141
Poliomyelitis in Tajikistan - Update
u' De los 32 casos confirmados por poliovirus salvajes, 17 son menores de 2 a\xf1os, 14 tienen entre 2 y 5 a\xf1os, y 1 tiene entre 6 y 15 a\xf1os. El 66% son del sexo masculino. De los casos de poliomielitis confirmados hasta la fecha, en 15 la par\xe1lisis comenz\xf3 en el mes de marzo, y en 17 en el mes de abril. Hay informaci\xf3n sobre los antecedentes vacunales de 21 de los 32 casos confirmados: 2 de ellos (10%) recibieron menos de tres dosis de vacuna antipoliomiel\xedtica oral (OPV), y los otros 19 (90%), tres dosis o m\xe1s.  Todos los casos se han registrado en el suroeste del pa\xeds, en una zona fronteriza con Afganist\xe1n y Uzbekist\xe1n que incluye la capital (Dushambe). La secuenciaci\xf3n gen\xe9tica ha revelado una estrecha relaci\xf3n entre este poliovirus y el de Uttar Pradesh (India).  El Gobierno de Tayikist\xe1n ha confirmado que, como respuesta al brote, tiene previstas tres rondas suplementarias de inmunizaci\xf3n dirigidas a todos los menores de 5 a\xf1os (aproximadamente 1,1 millones de ni\xf1os). Se utilizar\xe1 la vacuna antipoliomiel\xedtica oral monovalente frente al tipo 1 para obtener una inmunizaci\xf3n r\xe1pida de los ni\xf1os del pa\xeds. La primera ronda comenzar\xe1 el 1 de mayo en Dushambe y seis distritos vecinos. En otras regiones la vacunaci\xf3n de los menores de 5 a\xf1os comenzar\xe1 el 4 de mayo. Las otras dos rondas nacionales est\xe1n previstas para el 18 a 22 de mayo y el 1 a 5 de junio. Los pa\xedses vecinos est\xe1n respondiendo al brote con un reforzamiento de la vigilancia en todos los centros sanitarios y puntos de notificaci\xf3n, y est\xe1n examinando el estado inmunitario de los ni\xf1os. Uzbekist\xe1n (con una poblaci\xf3n de 2,89 millones de menores de 5 a\xf1os) est\xe1 planeando dos rondas de inmunizaci\xf3n suplementaria, tratando de sincronizarlas con las que se llevar\xe1n a cabo en Tayikist\xe1n en mayo y junio. En Kirguist\xe1n terminar\xe1 ma\xf1ana una campa\xf1a para potenciar la inmunidad de los ni\xf1os frente a las enfermedades prevenibles mediante vacunaci\xf3n, entre ellas la poliomielitis, que el Gobierno hab\xeda planificado como parte de la Semana Europea de Inmunizaci\xf3n. Kirguist\xe1n tiene previsto celebrar otros dos d\xedas de inmunizaci\xf3n a nivel subnacional, en zonas geogr\xe1ficas definidas. ', 'Tajikistan | Polio | Humans'
http://www.who.int/entity/csr/don/2010_04_29/es/index.html

Polio in Tajikistan - Update
' Of the 32 confirmed wild poliovirus cases, 17 are under the age of two years, 14 are between the ages of two and five years, and one is between the ages of six and 15 years. Sixty-six percent are male. To date, 15 of the confirmed polio cases had paralysis onset during March and 17 have had paralysis onset during April. Information on vaccination history is available for 21 of the 32 confirmed cases. Of these cases, 2 (10%) have reported to have received less than three doses of OPV and 19 (90%) received three or more doses of OPV.  All cases are reported from the south-west of the country, including the capital city Dushanbe. This region borders Afghanistan and Uzbekistan,. Genetic sequencing has now determined that the poliovirus is most closely related to virus from Uttar Pradesh, India.  In response to the outbreak, the government of Tajikistan confirmed they are planning three supplementary rounds of immunization targeting every child  ', 'Tajikistan | Polio | Humans'

Ongoing mumps outbreak in a student population with high ...
'Since December 2009, mumps incidence has increased in the Netherlands. As of 20 April 2010, 172 cases have been notified on the basis of laboratory confirmation or linkage to a laboratory-confirmed case. Of these, 112 were students, the majority of whom had been vaccinated (81%). Although outbreaks in vaccinated populations have been described before, risk factors for exposure and susceptibility, and dose-dependent vaccine effectiveness in a student population of this nature are relatively unknown.  ', 'Netherlands | Mumps | Humans'

Outbreak of poliomyelitis in Tajikistan in 2010: risk for ...
'On 23 April 2010, the World Health Organisation announced the confirmation of wild poliovirus serotype 1 (WPV1) in seven samples from children with Acute Flaccid Paralysis in Tajikistan, in the context of a multi-district cluster starting in December 2009. As of 28 April, 32 of 171 reported cases were laboratory-confirmed and most closely related to virus from Uttar Pradesh, India. This outbreak demonstrates the high risk that still exists for importation of wild poliovirus into polio-free regions. ', 'Tajikistan | Polio | Humans'

418161

HM Community News Reports
29 Apr 2010
Crimean-Congo Hemorrhagic Fever
Sudan
'13.831530','30.049950',5,96
Haemorrhagic fever confirmed in Sudan
u'Genetic analysis identifies human infections with haemorrhagic fever virus for the first time \nOutbreaks of suspected Crimean-Congo haemorrhagic fever (CCHF) have been occurring in the Kordufan region of Sudan over the past two years, but scientists could not say for sure whether the CCHF virus circulates in the country.\n \nMolecular tests on blood samples taken from patients during an outbreak affecting 12 people in 2008 have identified the virus for the first time in the country. The results of the analysis are published in the May edition of Emerging Infectious Diseases.\n \n\xe2\x80\x9cLaboratory confirmation of 8 cases of CCHF demonstrates the presence of this disease in Sudan,\xe2\x80\x9d write Imadeldin Aradaib, from the National Ribat University in Khartoum, and colleagues.\n \nCCHF is fatal for around 30% of people who contract it. It can be spread by the bite of an infected Hyalmoma tick. The ticks pick up the virus from infected animals and live in many parts of Africa, Asia, and southern Europe.\n \nThe incidence of the disease is rising in some parts of the world, including south-eastern Europe and Turkey, where scientists recently suggested that changes in the way land is used are behind the trend. They say the ticks can travel farther when natural habitats are separated by patches of bush left behind by human activity, and this enables the virus to circulate in a wider area.\n \nThe Sudanese outbreak was probably triggered when a butcher from Al-Fulah, a town in the central region of the country, picked up the CCHF virus from infected meat he handled, according to Aradaib and colleagues. He died after being admitted to the local hospital.\n \nThe virus spread to two nurses and two family members who cared for the man, the man\xe2\x80\x99s sister and a nurse who cared for her, say the authors. It also spread to three other people linked to the hospital. \xe2\x80\x9cNo protective gloves or antiseptic products were available at the hospital,\xe2\x80\x9d they add.\n \nA further three probable cases of the disease were spotted in the local community and in total nine people died in the outbreak. Laboratory tests confirmed the CCHF virus was behind the illness in eight cases, but it is not clear how many patients were included in the analysis.\n \n\xe2\x80\x9cGenetic analysis of the viruses showed that the strain involved was similar to strains found in South Africa, Mauritania, and Nigeria,\xe2\x80\x9d write Aradaib and colleagues. Understanding the lineages of the CCHF virus circulating in Sudan will help scientists to track the movement of the virus in the region and identify areas at risk of the disease, they add.\n \n\t\nReference and link \t \n\t\n1. \t\nAradaib IE, Erickson BR, Mustafa ME, Khristiva ML, Saeed NS, Elageb RM, et al. Nosocomial outbreak of Crimean-Congo haemorrhagic fever, Sudan. Emerg Infect Dis2010, 16:837\xe2\x80\x939. doi: 10.3201/eid1605.091815\nWorld Health Organization information about Crimean-Congo haemorrhagic fever ', 'Sudan | Crimean-Congo Hemorrhagic Fever | Humans'
http://www.eht-forum.org/news.html?fileId=news100429061451&from=home&id=0

HM Community News Reports
29 Apr 2010
E. coli
Daemen College, New York, United States
'42.964779','-78.788643',5,11639
Gastrointestinal Illness at a College Possibly Associated with a ...
'The Erie County Department of Health (ECDOH), in conjunction with the New York State Department of Health (NYSDOH) and the Niagara County Department of Health (NCDOH), is investigating a cluster of gastrointestinal illness at a local college. To date, 12 cases of gastrointestinal illness at Daemen College have been identified with onsets of illness from 4/12/10 through 4/17/10. Cases are between 18 and 28 years old, and all report eating at college dining facilities. Three of the cases were hospitalized and released. Five cases have reported bloody diarrhea, and one of these cases had E. coli 0145 detected in a stool specimen by the NYSDOH Wadsworth Center Laboratories. Pulsed-field gel electrophoresis (PFGE) testing of the specimen is pending.\nConcurrently, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), in conjunction with the Michigan (MI) and Ohio (OH) Departments of Health, are investigating outbreaks of E. coli O145 on two college campuses. MI is investigating 30+ suspect cases of bloody diarrhea with an age range between 18 and 32 years old and onset of illness from 4/9/10 through 4/16/10. E. coli 0145 and non-O157 have been isolated from clinical specimens, and specimens have multiple PFGE patterns. OH is investigating 11 cases of gastrointestinal illness with an age range between 18 and 44 years old with onset of illness from 4/11/10 through 4/15/10. Specimens from OH cases are a PFGE match to the main Michigan E. coli O145 pattern. Most ill persons report exposure to a student union/dining hall at the college.\nInvestigation of all clusters is ongoing, including investigation of possible food items associated with the outbreaks. PFGE results will determine if the Daemen College cases are related to those in Michigan and Ohio.\nPage 2 of 2\nE. coli non-0157 infections have emerged as an important cause of bloody diarrhea and hemolytic uremic syndrome (HUS). Infection commonly occurs through ingestion of the bacteria through contaminated food products such as beef (e.g. undercooked ground beef) and fresh produce (e.g. lettuce). Any food that can be contaminated by beef, cow manure, contaminated water, or an infected food handler may be a potential source of infection. Because the infectious dose is low, person-to-person transmission can be quite common, particularly in settings where hand washing facilities after toileting are inadequate. ', 'Daemen College, New York, United States | E. coli | Humans'
http://www.erie.gov/health/services/pdfs/272_ecoli_0145.pdf

['<img class=\\"f\\" src=\\"..\\/m\\" title=\\"Moreover Technologies\\" alt=\\"Moreover Technologies\\" \\/>', '29 Apr 2010', '<a href=\\"..\\/ai.php?417848&trto=en&trfr=en&pid234\\" class=\\"fbox\\">Mumps outbreak spreads among Rockland haredi<\\/a>', 'Mumps', '<a href=\\"javascript:sc(\'43.004601\',\'-75.498100\',5,234);\\">New York State, United States<\\/a>', 'Humans', 'null', 'null']

417848

Moreover Technologies
29 Apr 2010
Mumps
New York State, United States
'43.004601','-75.498100',5,234
Mumps outbreak spreads among Rockland haredi
'Rockland Jewish Reporter Adult Jewish Learning @ Midreshet Rockland Spring Courses 5770 Women\'s Division Mumps outbreak spreads among Rockland haredi Health officials are scrambling to contain a mumps outbreak that is sweeping haredi communities in New York and New Jersey. At least 1,500 people, mainly teenagers, have fallen ill from the virus which has been traced to a religious summer camp in Sullivan County. More than 300 cases have been confirmed in Rockland County. Dr Ira Oustatcher, the superintendent of schools for East Ramapo Central School District, said the disease appeared to be spreading mainly through yeshivas. However, the first case in a Rockland public school was reported, at Spring Valley High, at the beginning of February. Health officials are urging parents in the haredi community to ensure their children have been inoculated. Children should receive an MMR vaccine around the age of one. A second, follow-up dose is administered at about four years. Dr Oustatcher said East Ramapo Central School District organized a clinic earlier this month to offer free inoculations for staff and students who had missed one or both vaccinations. About 100 people attended. Other parents have taken children to their family doctor to be vaccinated. However, a small number of staff and students have refused vaccinations. Dr Oustatcher said they would be kept out of school because the health commissioner, Dr Joan Facelle, "has declared an outbreak." "When the health commissioner declares it\'s an outbreak you\'re not allowed in a school building for 25 days," said Dr Oustatcher. "The good news for us is that schools are closed for one week for President\'s Day and any time you can close a whole system for a week you are containing the potential to spread." The mumps outbreak has been traced to an 11-year-old boy from New York, who is believed to have picked up the virus while on holiday in England. He brought it to the Sullivan County summer camp last June, where 25 people, including children and staff members, fell ill. , the Center for Disease Control had confirmed about 200 cases of mumps, almost exclusively in haredi communities in New York and New Jersey. More than a dozen cases were also confirmed in the haredi community in Quebec, Canada. , confirmed mumps cases in New York and New Jersey reached 1,500. During the last major mumps outbreak, in 2006, 6,500 cases were reported. The disease is most commonly spread through coughing and sneezing. Symptoms, which include a fever and swollen glands, do not appear for about two weeks. In rare cases, complications can include deafness and male sterility.  So far, the virus has largely affected teenage boys, though in Orange County, patients have included a nine-month-old and a 60-year-old. A complicating factor has been the high number of mumps cases among people who have already been vaccinated. A spokesman for New York State health department said: "When mumps is introduced to a community that has not been exposed to it in many years, vaccinated people can be at risk of developing mumps. "This is particularly true in school settings, where the mumps virus can spread rapidly due to close contact between persons." According to New York State health department figures, almost 90 percent of recently infected children had received one dose of mumps vaccine and 75 percent had received the recommended two doses. Dr Oustatcher said that 40 percent of cases in East Ramapo Central School District were among students who had been inoculated. Tom Skinner, a spokesman for the Center for Disease Control said that the MMR vaccine\'s efficacy varies. "When you take into account this vaccine is from 60 to 90 percent effective and couple that with the fact that some people are not vaccinated, you can understand why something like this, once it gets into a community, can fester," he said. "But eventually, if vaccination rates are high enough, the virus will burn itself out." A recent CDC report suggested that the mumps virus had been largely contained within the haredi community because there is such "little interaction between members of the affected religious community and persons in surrounding communities." Roz Cohen, executive assistant to the CEO of Monsey Medical and Dental Center, said religious families were no less likely to have their children vaccinated than more secular families. But she did say that large families and large yeshiva classes probably allowed the virus to spread more quickly. A New York State health department spokesman emphasized that people who do not have contact with the haredi community are at very low risk of developing mumps. Nevertheless, he added: "Because an outbreak is occurring in your county, it would be prudent to see your doctor to make sure that your and your children\'s MMR vaccine coverage is up-to-date."  ', 'New York State, United States | Mumps | Humans', 'New Jersey, United States | Mumps | Humans'

But she did say that large families and large yeshiva classes probably allowed the virus to spread more quickly. A New York State health department spokesman emphasized that people who do not have contact with the haredi community are at very low risk of developing mumps. Nevertheless, he added: "Because an outbreak is occurring in your county, it would be prudent to see your doctor to make sure that your and your children\'s MMR vaccine coverage is up-to-date." Udupi: H1N1 Raises Ugly Head Again - Two Lose Lives
'Daijiworld Media Network - Udupi (SP) Udupi, Apr 28: The swine flu scare that had almost been forgotten has raised its heads again. 417256

HM Community News Reports
28 Apr 2010
Foot and Mouth
Ganghwa-gun, Incheon, South Korea
'37.747002','126.486000',5,11442
S. Korea confirms new outbreak of foot-and-mouth disease | YONHAP NEWS
u' Industry \nSEOUL, April 28 (Yonhap) -- The government on Wednesday confirmed the nation\'s ninth outbreak of foot-and-mouth disease this month at a pig farm west of Seoul. \xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0 The animals at the farm on Ganghwa Island, 60 kilometers from the capital city started showing symptoms late Tuesday, prompting on-site quarantine officials to order the culling and burying of all pigs raised there as a preventative step, the Ministry for Food, Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries said. \xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0 The ministry, which effectively raised the country\'s disease alert status to its highest level last week, is discouraging the movement of people, vehicles and animals near the site of the latest outbreak, hoping to help contain the disease. The farm, which raises 1,000 pigs, is located 3.1 kilometers from where the first outbreak was reported on April 8. \xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0 Farmers there recently noticed foot-and mouth symptoms -- blisters on the nose, mouth, teats and legs -- on some of the animals. \xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0 "Exactly how the animals became infected has not been determined, but a person responsible for artificial insemination, who visited a farm that reported an outbreak earlier in the month, may have spread the disease," an official said. While the normal incubation period for the animal virus is about two weeks, it can develop inside an animal for up to three weeks before symptoms start to show in rare cases, he added. \xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0 The outbreak is the first to be confirmed in the country since the two cases of the animal disease reported Thursday at another part of Ganghwa and in Chungju, located in the central part of the country. \xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0 Foot-and-mouth disease affects all cloven-hoofed animals such as cattle, pigs, deer, goats and buffalo and is classified as a "List A" disease by the Paris-based World Organization for Animal Health. Countries that report the disease are barred from exporting meat from cloven hoofed animals. \xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0 The farm is located in a relatively isolated part of the island with no livestock within a 500 meter radius, so no additional animals have to be culled, the ministry said. It, however, said an area up to 10 kilometers from the farm will be designated a special monitoring region so quarantine officials can check animals and take immediate action if a suspected case is found. \xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0 The government has ordered the culling of more than 42,000 heads of livestock on Ganghwa and in nearby Gimpo so far, with the total for the entire year exceeding 49,000 animals counting the latest outbreak. As of last week, compensation paid by the government to farmers reached 64.0 billion won (US$57.1 million). \xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0 The ministry said that in the future quarantine officials will be given the authority to order the culling of animals that may have been infected or order close observation regardless of distance from an outbreak site. \xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0 The country reported six outbreaks of foot-and-mouth disease in the Pocheon and Yeoncheon regions north of Seoul in January. \xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0 In the two previous outbreaks that hit the country in 2000 and 2002 the government ordered the culling of 2,216 and 5,956 animals at a cost of 300.6 billion won and 143.4 billion won, respectively. The higher compensation was due to a nationwide vaccination carried out to control the 2000 outbreak. \xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0 The ministry, meanwhile, said the latest outbreaks must be viewed separately from the outbreaks in January, noting the wide time gap and the fact that the latest cases involve a different strain of the virus. \xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0 All outbreaks confirmed in the first month of the year were of the A-Type strain, while those reported this month are O-Type, which spreads more quickly through swine. \xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0 yonngong@.kr  ', 'Ganghwa-gun, Incheon, South Korea | Foot and Mouth | Humans'
http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/business/2010/04/28/76/0501000000AEN20100428005200320F.HTML

Los Angeles officials warn against West Nile virus
' Los Angeles officials warn against West Nile virus \n LOS ANGELES, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Los Angeles officials warned on Tuesday that West Nile virus is posing a health threat to residents. \nResidents should take the threat of West Nile virus seriously given heavy seasonal rainfall and warm spring weather, the Greater Los Angeles County Vector Control District said in a statement. \nTwo dead birds in Los Angeles County tested positive for the virus, but no human cases have been reported, according to the agency. \nThe agency anticipates a busy season and urged residents to clean up stagnant water that has accumulated in ditches, drains, gutters, backyard containers and pools. Those areas are ideal for mosquito breeding.  ', 'Los Angeles, California, United States | West Nile Virus | Humans'

Flu vaccine convulsion cases in NZ
u' New Zealand children have suffered convulsions as officials scramble to gather information following reports of similar reactions to the flu vaccination in Australia. Several children under five-years-old in Western Australia suffered febrile convulsions - a fit caused by a high temperature - after receiving the influenza vaccine Fluvax as part of the state\'s free flu vaccination programme. Last week, the Ministry of Health here advised doctors against using Fluvax on children. Australia\'s chief medical officer gave the same advice to doctors in that country following concerns stemming from a significant rise in the number of children developing a fever after receiving the vaccine. Today New Zealand\'s Health Ministry chief advisor for child and youth health Pat Tuohy told politicians five children had been reported to have suffered febrile convulsions in New Zealand this year. The ministry was in regular contact with its Australian counterpart and a teleconference was scheduled for this afternoon to try and garner more information, he said. On present advice there was no reason for children, especially those at high risk, to stop receiving other types of flu vaccines, Dr Tuohy said. Children at a high risk were considered to be those who had an underlying chronic condition, such as asthma or diabetes, or those at risk for other reasons including those from low socio-economic families. While there had been more reports of severe reactions, including the five febrile convulsions, there were also more children receiving the vaccine and people were more likely to report reactions due to the media attention. Dr Tuohy said it was difficult to gather data and much of the information from Australia was from media reports. The ministry was trying to get more information so it could pass it on to the public. Dr Tuohy described the situation as "changing". Australia, New Zealand and Singapore were the only countries to use the vaccine so far this year. Most northern hemisphere countries begin flu vaccines in the lead up to winter. Over 260,000 Fluvax doses were administered in March and the ministry said supplies were now likely to be low. More supplies of alternative vaccine Vaxigrip were expected from Europe this week. Biebermania in New Zealand Send us your photos, videos and tip-offs: \xc2\xa9 2010 Fairfax New Zealand Limited XXXXXX Christchurch Press ', 'New Zealand | Vaccine Complication | Humans'

416753

HM Community News Reports
27 Apr 2010
Dengue
Kaohsiung City, Taiwan
'23.010872','120.666000',5,3144
Two more cases of indigenous dengue fever reported - CNA ENGLISH NEWS
"Taipei, April 27 (CNA) Two more cases of indigenous dengue fever have been reported in the southern city of Kaohsiung, bringing to five the total number of such cases recorded since the start of the dengue epidemic season in March, the Centers for Disease Control (CDC) said Monday. The latest cases, reported within a week, were classified as a cluster infection involving two people who live 15 meters away from each other in the city's Lingya district, according to CDC Director-General Ling Ting. The three previous cases also occurred in the port city. Lin said this year's dengue fever epidemic pattern is similar to that of 2002 in that the season started early, which raises concerns that the outbreak this year could be as bad as it was in 2002. In 2002, a total of 5,336 cases of indigenous dengue fever were recorded. The number included 241 cases of hemorrhagic fever, a potentially fatal development of the mosquito-borne disease, and 21 deaths. This year's epidemic season began in the 11th week -- three weeks earlier than in 2002, Lin noted. The interval between the start of the 2010 epidemic season and the end of the 2009 epidemic season was four weeks, which was two weeks shorter than that between 2002 and 2001, he added. (.F. Low) ENDITEM /pc  ", 'Kaohsiung City, Taiwan | Dengue | Humans'

Poliomyelitis in Tajikistan: First import from the certification of ...
u' Au 21 avril 2010, 120 cas de paralysie flasque aigu\xeb avaient \xe9t\xe9 notifi\xe9s au Tadjikistan. Pour la majorit\xe9 d\u2019entre eux, la paralysie s\u2019est manifest\xe9e dans les deux derni\xe8res semaines, ce qui a amen\xe9 les autorit\xe9s du pays \xe0 notifier \xe0 l\u2019OMS une flamb\xe9e \xe9pid\xe9mique. Dix de ces enfants sont d\xe9c\xe9d\xe9s. Dans l\u2019immense majorit\xe9 des cas, il s\u2019agit d\u2019enfants de moins de 5 ans. Les donn\xe9es pr\xe9liminaires semblent indiquer que plus de 45 % d\u2019entre eux avaient re\xe7u quatre doses ou plus de vaccin antipoliomy\xe9litique buccal. Jusqu\u2019\xe0 pr\xe9sent, le poliovirus de type 1 a \xe9t\xe9 isol\xe9 dans des \xe9chantillons de diagnostic provenant de 7 de ces cas. Tous sont situ\xe9s au sud-ouest du pays, dans une r\xe9gion \xe0 la fronti\xe8re de l\u2019Afghanistan et de l\u2019Ouzb\xe9kistan. L\u2019Afghanistan est l\u2019un des quatre derniers pays d\u2019end\xe9mie. Aucun cas n\u2019a \xe9t\xe9 notifi\xe9 en Afghanistan, dans les zones \xe0 la fronti\xe8re du Tadjikistan.  Le gouvernement du Tadjikistan a demand\xe9 \xe0 l\u2019OMS des orientations et une assistance technique. Des vaccins pour trois campagnes de riposte \xe0 la flamb\xe9e sont mis en place par la Division des approvisionnements de l\u2019UNICEF au Tadjikistan. Le dernier cas clinique confirm\xe9 de poliomy\xe9lite au Tadjikistan s\u2019\xe9tait produit en 1997 et le dernier cas confirm\xe9 par analyse virologique remonte en 1991. Le chiffre d\xe9clar\xe9 par les autorit\xe9s pour la couverture par trois doses de VPO \xe9tait de 87 % en 2008, derni\xe8re ann\xe9e pour laquelle ont dispose de donn\xe9es compl\xe8tes dans le cadre de la proc\xe9dure conjointe OMS/UNICEF. Les indicateurs de la surveillance de la PFA au Tadjikistan r\xe9pondent aux normes de la certification au niveau national. En 2009, le Tadjikistan a notifi\xe9 35 cas de paralysie flasque aigu\xeb, aucun d\xfb \xe0 un poliovirus sauvage. \xc0 l\u2019\xe9chelle mondiale, plus de 90 000 cas de paralysie flasque aigu\xeb ont \xe9t\xe9 notifi\xe9s en 2009, dont 1606 dus \xe0 des poliovirus sauvages. ', 'Tajikistan | Polio | Humans'

ReliefWeb \u00bb Document \u00bb Zimbabwe: Measles and cholera cases a headache ...
u'\xa0\xa0|\xa0\xa0 Contact \n Zimbabwe: Measles and cholera cases a headache in Buhera \nBUHERA - Buhera has seen 12 measles deaths in the past two weeks and more than 60 cases of cholera recorded in the area. \n About 36 villagers were treated for cholera at Murambinda Hospital and discharged while two more cases of the deadly cholera disease were detected in Chipinge and Chimanimani, respectively. Six children died in the Dekeya area under Chief Nyashanu. They were understood to have been buried secretly by their parents, who belong to the Johane Marange Apostolic Sect, which shuns modern health treatment. The sect believes in using prayer and water to heal the sick. In Makoni and Buhera, religious and cultural radicalism continue militating against emergency health interventions meant to combat the viral measles disease, whose symptoms include drowsiness, coughing, loss of appetite, gradual elevation of temperature, body rash on the inner cheek, high fever and recurrence rash.\n Chief Chiduku in Makoni district recently accused the Measles Task Teams in the district of corrupting their religious beliefs through coerced vaccination of sect children. The acrimony deepened with the traditional leader accusing the all-male Task Team of "snatching their sect wives" under the guise of an immunisation crackdown. In an interview with The Zimbabwean last week, the Manicaland Medical Director, Dr Milton Chemhuru, said the situation was under control. Chemhuru said: "We are on the verge of rolling an indiscriminate vaccination campaign for all children between six months and 14 months. The campaigns will be without exception. We want parents to adhere to prescribed child immunisation schedules." ', 'Buhera District, Zimbabwe | Measles | Humans', 'Buhera District, Zimbabwe | Cholera | Humans'

In an interview with The Zimbabwean last week, the Manicaland Medical Director, Dr Milton Chemhuru, said the situation was under control. HM Community News Reports
26 Apr 2010
Influenza H1N1
Lalang, South Sumatra, Indonesia
'-2.900000','104.583336',5,11596
(Indonesian) Avian Influenza suspected in 3 toddlers
u' Peningkatan Mutu Pendidikan harus Dari Dasar \n Kita masih melakukan observasi terhadap korban yang mengalami demam panas tinggi disertai batuk dan sakit kepala serta tubuh terasa sakit. Apakah terjangkit virus flu burung atau tidak \n Kepala Puskesmas Sungai Apit \n - Ratusan ekor ayam milik warga Desa Lalang Kecamatan Sungai Apit sejak beberapa hari terakhir ini ditemukan mati mendadak. Kematian ayam ini membuat warga panik dan melaporkan kejadian tersebut ke petugas Puskesmas Sungai Apit. Bahkan kematian ayam ini sempat membuat tiga balita demam panas. Diduga tiga balita itu terinveksi virus flu burung. Petugas Puskesmas bersama petugas dari Dinas Peternakan, Perikanan dan Pertanian (Distanakan) Siak yang turun ke lokasi, Minggu (25/4), sempat menemukan kejanggalan terhadap kematian ayam tersebut. Tim medis yang dipimpin, drh Romi dari Distanakan Siak juga sudah mengambil sampel ayam yang mati untuk dilakukan rapid tes. Setelah dilakukan penelitian, ayam yang mati mendadak tersebut positif terinfeksi virus flu burung. Kepala Puskesmas Sungai Apit, dr Hartini saat dikonfirmasi mengatakan, ayam milik warga Desa Lalang yang mati mendadak tersebut memang positif terinfeksi virus flu burung. Hal ini diketahui setelah, drh Romi dari Dinas Peternakan melakukan rapid tes terhadap ayam yang mati mendadak tersebut. "Untuk\xc2\xa0 memberi pengetahuan kepada masyarakat tentang bahaya flu burung dan bagaimana cara penanganannya, pihak Puskesmas akan melakukan sosialisasi ke warga Desa Lalang dalam waktu dekat," kata Hartini, Senin (26/4). Sementara itu, tiga balita dan satu orang warga yang diduga terjangkit virus flu burung sudah dirawat intensif di Puskesmas dan kondisinya sudah berangsur pulih. Keempat balita dan satu orang warga RT 03 RW 05 Dusun 2, Desa Lalang masing-masing bernama Muhammad Sandika Putra (3,9 ), Jumiati (3,6 ), Zurahmah (3,4) dan Efriadi (34). Saat ini ketiga balita itu masih dirawat intensif di Puskesmas Sungai Apit. Kepala Dinas Kesehatan Siak, Ir H Budiman Shafari mengatakan, pihaknya sudah meminta petugas kesehatan untuk memantau lokasi ditemukan ayam mati. Bahkan untuk mencegah wabah tersebut, warga diingatkan agar tidak menyentuh ayam yang mati, khususnya bagi anak-anak di bawah umur yang rentan terhadap jangkitan virus tersebut. (*) Penulis: Fendi, Siak \n (37) Dibaca -  ', 'Lalang, South Sumatra, Indonesia | Influenza H1N1 | Humans'
http://metroriau.com/read-1635-2010-04-26-tiga-balita-diduga-suspek-flu-burung.html

Poliomyelitis in Tajikistan since the first import certified the ...
u' A fecha del 21 de abril de 2010 se hab\xedan notificado 120 casos de PFA en Tayikist\xe1n. En la mayor\xeda de ellos la par\xe1lisis apareci\xf3 en las dos \xfaltimas semanas, lo que ha llevado al Gobierno a notificar un brote a la OMS. Diez ni\xf1os han fallecido. La mayor\xeda de los casos son menores de 5 a\xf1os. Los datos preliminares indican que m\xe1s del 45% de ellos hab\xedan recibido cuatro o m\xe1s dosis de vacuna antipoliomiel\xedtica oral. Hasta la fecha se han aislado poliovirus de tipo 1 en muestras diagn\xf3sticas de siete de estos casos. Todos los casos se han registrado en el suroeste del pa\xeds, en una zona fronteriza con Afganist\xe1n y Uzbekist\xe1n. Afganist\xe1n es uno de los cuatro pa\xedses en los que la poliomielitis sigue siendo end\xe9mica, pero no se han notificado casos en las zonas de Afganist\xe1n fronterizas con Tayikist\xe1n.  El Gobierno de Tayikist\xe1n ha solicitado a la OMS orientaci\xf3n y apoyo t\xe9cnico. La Divisi\xf3n de Suministros del UNICEF ha empezado a depositar vacunas para tres rondas de respuesta al brote en Tayikist\xe1n.  El \xfaltimo caso de poliomielitis confirmado cl\xednicamente en Tayikist\xe1n se registr\xf3 en 1997, y el \xfaltimo confirmado mediante pruebas virol\xf3gicas, en 1991. La cobertura nacional con la vacuna OPV3 fue del 87% en 2008, \xfaltimo a\xf1o sobre el que hay datos completos obtenidos mediante el proceso de notificaci\xf3n conjunto OMS/UNICEF. Los indicadores de la vigilancia de la PFA en Tayikist\xe1n cumplen las normas de certificaci\xf3n a nivel nacional. En 2009 Tayikist\xe1n notific\xf3 35 casos de PFA, ninguno de ellos causado por poliovirus salvajes. En todo el mundo se notificaron m\xe1s de 90 000 casos de PFA en 2009, de los cuales 1606 fueron causados por poliovirus salvajes. ', 'Tajikistan | Polio | Humans'

New Mexico Confirms Another Case of Plague in Pets
u' The New Mexico Department of Health\xe2\x80\x99s Scientific Laboratory confirmed plague this week in a dog that lived near San Jon in Quay County (photo: James Orr). \n The New Mexico Department of Health\xe2\x80\x99s Scientific Laboratory confirmed plague this week in a dog that lived near San Jon in Quay County. Other confirmed animal plague cases this year include a dog and cat from Santa Fe County (city of Santa Fe and Eldorado) and a dog and cat from Rio Arriba County (Alcalde and Abiquiu area). All cases have recovered. No human plague or Hantavirus cases have been confirmed so far this year. \n \xe2\x80\x9cThe increased winter and spring precipitation can stimulate increases in rodent populations and lead to increased plague and Hantavirus activity,\xe2\x80\x9d Ettestad said. \xe2\x80\x9cPlague cases in pets serve as a warning that there is plague activity in rodents and their fleas, and human cases can follow. Pets infected with plague are hunters who have eaten an infected rodent or been bitten by a rodent\xe2\x80\x99s fleas prior to getting ill. Pets can transport the fleas back into the home where they can infect people.\xe2\x80\x9d \n In New Mexico, there were six human cases of plague in 2009: three from Santa Fe County, two from Bernalillo County and one from Sandoval County. One of the Santa Fe County cases was a fatal case in an 8-year-old boy. \n Four cases of Hantavirus occurred in New Mexico in 2009, one each from Rio Arriba, Taos, Santa Fe, and San Miguel counties. None were fatal. Two cases of Hantavirus occurred in New Mexico in 2008, one each from Taos and Otero counties. Both of which were fatal.  ', 'New Mexico, United States | Plague | Humans'
http://www.pctonline.com/new-mexico-plague-pets.aspx

415519

HM Community News Reports
25 Apr 2010
Mumps
Guam [USA]
'13.444400','144.736603',6,377
DHSS: 100 Cases of Mumps Since January
u'Guam - Since January 2010, over 100 cases of mumps have been reported to Guam Department of Health and Social Services. New cases are being reported daily and this case count will continue to increase. Cases have been reported from numerous communities and villages around Guam. \n Mumps is a viral illness that can cause fever, headache, muscle aches, tiredness and painful swelling of the salivary glands under the ears. Rarely, people may have complications from mumps including painful swelling of the testicles in males after puberty, deafness, or swelling in or around the brain. Mumps can be spread from person-to-person through oral or respiratory secretions. Guam DPHSS urges the public to make sure that their shots are up to date to prevent mumps and other diseases. Although two doses of Measles, Mumps, Rubella (MMR) vaccine offers the best protection against mumps (with 90% vaccine effectiveness), a small number of people can still get mumps even if they have been vaccinated. People who are not fully vaccinated are at higher risk of getting mumps. In order to stop the spread of mumps on Guam, Guam DPHSS is working on finding and interviewing cases, assessing risk factors, and developing the best response to stop this outbreak. A team from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention is assisting Guam DPHSS in this important work. The public is asked to report any illnesses with facial swelling to Guam DPHSS (see number below) and to have people sick with these symptoms stay home from work, school, or gatherings until 5 days after the swelling began.\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0 In addition, Guam DPHSS will soon begin calling some doctors\xe2\x80\x99 offices daily to check on any new mumps cases that may have been seen. Thank you for helping to protect our community by reporting any current or recent cases of illness with the above symptoms in your family. This information will help Guam DPHSS put in place the best possible interventions to prevent illness. Ways the public can keep their families healthy: 1)\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0 Make sure your family members are fully immunized with the Measles, Mumps and Rubella (MMR) vaccine. 2)\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0 Have people sick with mumps symptoms stay home from school, work, and gatherings until 5 days after facial swelling began. 3)\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0 Wash your hands with soap and water frequently, avoid sharing eating or drinking utensils, clean frequently touched surfaces, minimize contact with sick persons, cover your cough with a tissue or sleeve. 4)\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0 Report current or recent cases of facial swelling to the number below. A public health staff person will ask a few questions that will help Guam DPHSS stop this outbreak. Ways that the medical community can help: 1)\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0 Report ALL cases of acute onset of unilateral or bilateral tender, self-limited swelling of the parotid or other salivary gland(s), without other apparent cause. 2)\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0 If your office is selected to participate in daily reporting of these cases, please have your staff compile a list of names of patients seen with these symptoms every day. A public health staff person will call to ask for information on the cases recorded the previous day. 3)\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0 Remember that mumps can occur in persons who have been vaccinated. 4)\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0 Do not wait for test results before reporting suspected mumps cases to Guam DPHSS. Mumps IgM results may be negative during mumps infection, especially in previously vaccinated individuals. Suspected Mumps Cases should be reported to Guam DPHSS Immunization Program at: Phone: 735-7143, or Fax 734-1475. Written by : \n Trackback (0) \n TrackBack URI for this entry\n Write comment  ', 'Guam [USA] | Mumps | Humans'
http://www.pacificnewscenter.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4559:dhss-100-cases-of-mumps-since-january&catid=45:guam-news&Itemid=156

Equine virus reported | Massachusetts news | \n projo.com | The ...
u"[an error occurred while processing this directive]\n[an error occurred while processing this directive]\n Children's Holiday Hope Fund \n 01:00 AM EDT on Thursday, April 22, 2010 \nPROVIDENCE \u2013\u2013 Horse owners and breeders in Rhode Island are being advised of an outbreak of a contagious equine virus in New Jersey and neighboring Massachusetts. Though the virus does not pose a risk to humans, the virus can survive up to several weeks in cold, damp weather and cause respiratory illness, spontaneous abortion, neurological disease and death in horses. The current outbreak has been linked to four horses that were exposed to the EHV-1 virus in New Jersey and subsequently transported to Massachusetts. Effective vaccines are available and horse owners should discuss a vaccination with their veterinarian. Newly acquired horses should be isolated from other horses for a minimum of seven days. Richard C. '38.528179','71.042000',5,141
Polio in Tajikistan, first importation since Europe certified ...
" As of 21 April 2010, 120 cases of acute flaccid paralysis had been reported from Tajikistan. The majority of these have onset of paralysis within the past 2 weeks, prompting the Government to notify WHO of an outbreak. Ten of the children have died. The vast majority of the cases are children 45% had four or more doses of oral polio vaccine.  To date, poliovirus type 1 has been isolated in diagnostic specimens from 7 of these cases. All cases are in the south-west of the country, in an area bordering Afghanistan and Uzbekistan. Afghanistan is one of the four remaining polio-endemic countries. No cases have been reported in the areas of Afghanistan bordering Tajikistan.  The Government of Tajikistan has requested technical guidance and support from WHO. Vaccine for three outbreak response rounds is being pre-positioned by UNICEF Supply Division for Tajikistan.  Tajikistan's last case of clinically confirmed polio was in 1997; the last case of polio confirmed by virological testing was in 1991. Reported OPV3 coverage nationwide was 87% in 2008, the last year for which complete data are available under the WHO/UNICEF joint reporting process. AFP surveillance indicators in Tajikistan meet certification standards at the national level. In 2009, Tajikistan reported 35 cases of acute flaccid paralysis, of which none were caused by wild poliovirus. Globally, more than 90,000 cases of acute flaccid paralysis were reported in 2009, of which 1606 were caused by wild poliovirus. ", 'Tajikistan | Polio | Humans'
http://www.who.int/entity/csr/don/2010_04_23/en/index.html

' Singapore reports increase of hand-foot-mouth disease \n SINGAPORE, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Singapore reported a total of 572 hand-foot-mouth disease (HFMD) cases last week, up by 30 compared to the week before. \nLocal TV broadcaster Channel NewsAsia said on Wednesday that the number of HFMD cases here has been hovering around warning levels in the past two months. \nThe government is conducting spot checks on some 800 childcare centers to ensure that they have put in place measures to prevent an outbreak. \nHFMD usually infects children and infants. Symptoms include fever, ulcers in the throat and rashes on the hands and feet. HFMD is spread from person to person by direct contact through the nasal discharge, saliva, faeces and fluid from the rash of an infected person. Dengue

'24.554592','-81.791481',5,7852
Denge fever reappears in Key West
' \'.\' => \' | Registration | [/mi/registration/request/user_run_mode]\' } --> \n With the first case of the mosquito-borne illness dengue fever reported in the Keys since mid-October, Monroe County health officials are warning Key West residents to take precautions.</p><p>The most recent case, reported in a 41-year-old member of the U.S. Navy, was confirmed through lab tests in Miami after the man initially sought treatment from military doctors on April 6.</p><p>Officials believe the case was contracted locally, as the man reported no out-of-country travel in the past year.</p><p>Naval Air Station Key West spokesman Jim Brooks confirmed that the man, whom officials didn\'t identify, lived in base housing in Key West and that "areas where he lived and worked have been tested and sprayed."</p><p>"What we\'re going to do right now," Monroe County Health Department spokesman Chris Tittel said, "is continue that push of the public health message that people need to be aware on a very personal level of how to deal with mosquitoes."</p><p>That includes dumping standing water around homes, screening doors and windows, using air-conditioning whenever possible and regularly wearing DEET or other repellants.</p><p>"We had hoped we\'d be able to eliminate the disease from Key West and took every effort to do so," Health Department Administrator Bob Eadie said. "However, the confirmed case is not totally unexpected in that once dengue fever has been established in an area, it is truly almost impossible to completely eradicate it."</p><p>An initial outbreak last June -- the first cases documented in Florida in 40 years -- prompted researchers at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention dengue lab in Puerto Rico to blood test some 240 cooperative Old Town residents. The survey found that 99 people tested positive for dengue or associated antibodies.</p><p>Symptoms include high fever, aching bones, headaches, pain behind the eyes and a rash. More than 100 million people worldwide have contracted the disease, which is endemic in some tropical areas including Puerto Rico and Central America.\n Middle Keys Attractions \n Lower Keys Attractions \n Key West Attractions  ', 'Key West, Florida, United States | Dengue | Humans'
http://www.keysnet.com/2010/04/21/211818/denge-fever-reappears-in-key-west.html

Update on cluster of Rotavirus cases in a Queen Elizabeth Hospital ...
u' Update on cluster of Rotavirus cases in a Queen Elizabeth Hospital neonatal ward \n ********************************************************** \n The following is issued on behalf of the Hospital Authority: \xa0\xa0\xa0\xa0\xa0The spokesperson of Queen Elizabeth Hospital (QEH) made the following update today (April 21) regarding an earlier announcement on a number of the Rotavirus cases in the neonatal ward: \xa0\xa0\xa0\xa0\xa0One more newborn male infant (aged 7 days) has presented with diarrhea symptoms in the neonatal ward. "  The first case is a 22 year old male from Nhu Co commune, Bac Kan province. He developed symptoms on the 28 of March 2010 and was transferred to the National Hospital of Tropical Diseases in severe condition. Confirmatory test results for influenza A (H5) were obtained on 3 April.   The initial epidemiological investigations show that there were sick/dead poultry at the patient's home and in the surrounding areas.  The second case is a 2 year old girl residing in Cho Moi district, Bac Kan province. She developed symptoms on 2 April 2010. On 4 April, she was transferred to Cho Moi District Hospital for treatment where she is in a stable condition. Confirmatory test results for influenza A (H5) were obtained on 7 April. 412712

World Org. for Animal Health
20 Apr 2010
Foot and Mouth
Japan
'36.098541','138.478607',5,156
Japan : Foot and mouth disease
u'Report date : 2010-04-20 14:20:20Country : JapanDisease: : Foot and mouth disease\n\nA private veterinarian first found a suspicious case in the affected farm and reported it to the local government\xe2\x80\x99s veterinary service on 9 April 2010. An official veterinarian observed that a cow had fever, anorexia, salivation and erosions in the oral cavity on the same day but the others had no clinical signs. Since other two suspicious cases were found in the same farm on 16 April, the veterinary service examined similar diseases such as bluetongue, bovine viral diarrhoea-mucosal disease (BVD-MD), infectious bovine rhinotracheitis and Ibaraki disease but they showed negative results by PCR tests on 19 April 2010. The veterinary service submitted the samples to the National Institute for Animal Health (NIAH) on the same day. The NIAH affirmed the cattle were infected with foot and mouth disease virus by PCR test on 20 April 2010. The samples are being examined by virus isolation. If it is confirmed, it will be the first outbreak of foot and mouth disease in Japan since 2000. All cattle in the affected farm were destroyed. Disinfection of affected premises is being implemented. Movement restrictions within 10km around the affected farm have been implemented. Export international veterinary certificates for ruminants and products derived from them have been suspended since 20 April 2010.  ', 'Japan | Foot and Mouth | Humans'
http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=9155&newlang=en

USA - Bovine TB
' 16 Apr 2010 \n Nebraska agriculture officials say they have found a new case of bovine tuberculosis in the northeast corner of the state. Nebraska Agriculture Director Greg Ibach (eye-baw) said Wednesday the new case was uncovered in Cedar County as part of the investigation of a case of the illness found in South Dakota. \n Ibach also says the Nebraska investigation into bovine tuberculosis that began last June after two cases were found in a Rock County herd has concluded with no additional cases. Nebraska officials tested nearly 22,000 cattle after the two cases were found last year, and three herds remain quarantined as part of that investigation. EuroSurveillance
15 Apr 2010
Dengue
Comoros
'-11.892760','43.675919',5,175
Dengue type 3 virus infections in European travellers returning ...
'In late February-early April 2010, five cases of dengue fever were diagnosed in returning travellers in Europe in EurotravNet sites in Sweden and France in patients with travel history to the Comoros and/or Zanzibar, Tanzania. Four cases were non-complicated dengue fever and one case dengue hemorrhagic fever. Three patients were viraemic at the time of diagnosis and infected with Dengue type 3 virus. \n\nAn estimated 100 million cases of dengue fever and 250,000 cases of dengue haemorrhagic fever occur annually worldwide [1]. The past 20 years have seen a dramatic geographic expansion of epidemic dengue fever from Southeast Asia to the South Pacific Islands, the Caribbean, and the Americans. An increasing number of reports of dengue fever and associated illness among travellers to dengue virus-infected areas paralleled the changing epidemiology of dengue in local populations [1].\nIn 2010 (until 14 April), five cases of dengue fever including one case of dengue haemorrhagic fever, have been reported from EurotravNet sites in France and Sweden, in four travellers returning from the Comoros and one traveller returning from Zanzibar, Tanzania. EurotravNet, the Network for travel medicine and tropical diseases of the European Centre for Disease Control consists of 14 core sites in nine European countries and participants monitor travel related infectious diseases in Europe (www.eurotravnet.eu). ', 'Comoros | Dengue | Humans', 'Zanzibar, Tanzania | Dengue | Humans'
http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ViewArticle.aspx?ArticleId=19541

14 Apr 2010
Respiratory Illness
Castle Peak Hospital, Tuen Mun, Hong Kong
'22.409241','113.971565',5,11382
Update on cluster of parainfluenza virus cases in mixed ...
u' Update on cluster of parainfluenza virus cases in mixed rehabilitation ward at Castle Peak Hospital \n ******************************************************** \n The following is issued on behalf of the Hospital Authority: \xa0\xa0\xa0\xa0\xa0Regarding a mixed rehabilitation ward at Castle Peak Hospital (CPH) in which some patients had tested positive for parainfluenza virus (PIV) type 3, the hospital spokesperson announced the following update today (April 14): \xa0\xa0\xa0\xa0\xa0One more male patient and one staff member in the ward have presented with respiratory symptoms. Appropriate tests were arranged for the 68-year-old patient and the results are pending. The patient is being treated under isolation and is in stable condition. The staff member is on sick leave. \xa0\xa0\xa0\xa0\xa0Admission to the ward has been suspended. Restricted visits to and discharge from the ward have been imposed. Infection control measures of the ward concerned have been stepped up. All other patients in the ward are under close surveillance. \xa0\xa0\xa0\xa0\xa0The cases have been reported to the Hospital Authority Head Office and the Centre for Health Protection for follow up. \n Ends/Wednesday, April 14, 2010 Issued at HKT 18:43  ', 'Castle Peak Hospital, Tuen Mun, Hong Kong | Respiratory Illness | Humans'

Caritas Medical Centre, Cheung Sha Wan, Hong Kong
'22.341867','114.154060',5,11381
Cluster of respiratory syncytial virus cases in Development ...
u' Cluster of respiratory syncytial virus cases in Development Disabilities Unit in Caritas Medical Centre \n ************************************************************ \n The following is issued on behalf of the Hospital Authority: \xa0\xa0\xa0\xa0\xa0The Caritas Medical Centre (CMC) spokesperson made the following announcement today (April 14): \xa0\xa0\xa0\xa0\xa0Four residents (three male and one female, aged six to 13) on one of the floors in the Development Disabilities Unit (DDU) of the CMC have presented with fever and respiratory symptoms since April 8. The hospital arranged appropriate clinical tests for these children. Three of them are positive for respiratory syncytial virus. The four residents are being treated under isolation and are in stable condition. \xa0\xa0\xa0\xa0\xa0Infection control measures have been stepped up in DDU. New admission is suspended while visiting arrangements remain unchanged. All other child residents in the unit are under close surveillance. \xa0\xa0\xa0\xa0\xa0The cases have been reported to the Hospital Authority Head Office and the Centre for Health Protection. \n Ends/Wednesday, April 14, 2010 Issued at HKT 18:57  ', 'Caritas Medical Centre, Cheung Sha Wan, Hong Kong | Respiratory Syncytial Virus | Humans'

Hand-foot-mouth disease claims 94 lives in China
' Hand-foot-mouth disease claims 94 lives in China \n BEIJING, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Ninety-four children had died of the hand-foot-mouth disease (HFMD) this year in China as of Sunday, a spokesman with the Ministry of Health said Wednesday. \nMore than 192,300 cases, including 2,119 serious cases, were reported in the country from Jan. 1 to April 11, a rise of almost 40 percent from the same period last year, ministry spokesman Deng Haihua told Xinhua. \nAbout 80 percent of the cases happened in the provinces of Guangdong, Henan, Guangxi, Zhejiang, Jiangsu, Anhui, Sichuan, Hubei, Hunan and Shandong. The deaths occurred in 18 provinces, said Deng. \nSpring was a high-risk period for HFMD, experts have warned.  ', 'China | Hand, Foot and Mouth Disease | Humans'

White nose syndrome

'43.675800','-71.499100',5,231
White nose syndrome takes toll on N.H. bats
"April 13, 2010 A mysterious disease is decimating New Hampshire's bat population. A winter survey of the state's bats shows white nose syndrome is taking a toll on five of the state's eight species. Wildlife officials say the statewide bat population is down 66 percent since last year. In in ice-sealed mine in Grafton County, the survey showed 96 bats died and others showed signs of the disease. However in a smaller, heavily flooded mine, the population increased by 12 and there was very little sign of the disease. White nose syndrome was first discovered in a New York cave in 2006. It has now spread to at least 11 states, including Vermont. Vermont Sen. Patrick Leahy recently urged the U.S. Interior Department to increase funding for research into white nose syndrome. He said there's danger the disease will spread across the country. ", 'New Hampshire, United States | White nose syndrome | Bats'

RECORD STORMS COULD BRING RECORD MOSQUITOES
u' AWAY FROM YOUR PC? KEEP IN TOUCH WITH NBC40 mobile ! CHECK NBC40 mobile FOR LATEST NJ TRANSIT DELAYS AND CANCELLATIONS! MISS THE NEWS? WATCH SOUTH JERSEY\'S TOP LOCAL STORIES HERE ON ! VIEW DAN SKELDON\'S WEATHER CLASS VISITS ON \'s WEATHER PAGE! CATCH UP ON THE THE DAY\'S ECONOMIC NEWS WITH CNBC -- NOW ON \'s FINANCIAL PAGE! \n CAPE MAY COUNTY-- Dr. Peter Bosak and the rest of the Cape May County Mosquito Control Team are worried. "This is by far the worst year I have seen," said Bosak the Mosquito Control Superintendent. They are worried that year full of record\xc2\x96breaking snow and rain could now bring a record number of mosquitoes. "It\'s certainly a no\xc2\x96brainer. More water means more mosquitoes," said Bosak. With more places than ever to breed, mosquito larvae are filling flooded areas. "Because we have so many mosquito larvae present they obviously could turn into millions of adult mosquitoes that are going to cause nuisance throughout the county," said Bosak. With all this standing water crews are fighting to stop the 47 different species of mosquitoes that reside in Cape May County. There are over 60 statewide. Now they are busier then ever trying to stop the bugs before they can attack. "A lot of these areas are close to suburban neighborhoods. These adults will then take off from these wooden habitats and fly into these neighborhoods and start\xc2\x96biting people," said Bosak. With a grim mosquito season outlook, Dr. Bosak and his team are doing everything they can to eliminate the pests. Crews are spraying flooded areas with a biological pesticide that they say can kill mosquito larvae in just hours. "Our biggest challenge at this point is really just trying to keep up with controlling the larvae that are out there," said Bosak. A part of the process is collecting samples and sending them to a lab. This is where experts take a closer look to identify different species and breeding patterns, but with such a widespread problem crews are finding themselves stuck in the mud. "I am concerned because there is a lot more water then we\'re used to. We do have a finite number of people we can employ to take care of this and obviously its much more then we\'re used to," said Bosak. Experts say it\'s too early to tell which mosquitoes carry the dangerous West Nile Virus. They advise residents to try to remove standing water from around their homes and to contact your local mosquito control center with any questions or concerns. \n \xc2\xa9 2010 ACCESS.1 COMMUNICATIONS and WMGM-TV Contact Us  ', 'New Jersey, United States | Environmental | Humans'

300 children suffering from mysterious disease in Muzaffarpur
u' 300 children suffering from mysterious disease in Muzaffarpur \nAbout 300 children fell sick after mysterious disease afflicted them at different places in the district during the past one week. Official sources said here today about 300 children were admitted to different Public Health Centres as they were suffering with a mysterious disease which was yet to be ascertained. Head of the Department of Medicine in Srikrishna Medical College Hospital Dr Brajmohan said all such patients had symptoms matching with that of Encephalitis Syndrome. Samples of some patients had been sent for laboratory test which would confirm nature of the ailment. Meanwhile, District Civil Surgeon Dr Arjun Prasad said he had directed all the hospitals, including the Primary Health Centres, to refer such patients to Patna Medical College Hospital. '15.361170','18.664480',5,57
Meningococcal disease in Chad
u' Les analyses par test de latex de 67 \xe9chantillons de liquide c\xe9phalorachidien ont \xe9t\xe9 positives pour le s\xe9rogroupe A de Neisseria meningitidis et celles de 14 \xe9chantillons ont \xe9t\xe9 positives pour le s\xe9rogroupe W 135 de Neisseria meningitidis au test de latex et \xe0 la culture. Cela indique des \xe9pid\xe9mies mixtes dans certaines zones (Dono-Manga), tandis que dans d\u2019autres, soit le s\xe9rogroupe A (districts de Doba et B\xe9bidja), soit le s\xe9rogroupe W135 (district de Goundi) est pr\xe9dominant.  Le Groupe international de coordination pour l\u2019approvisionnement en vaccin antim\xe9ningococcique (GIC) pour la lutte contre la m\xe9ningite \xe9pid\xe9mique a fourni 157 000 doses de vaccin trivalent ACW pour une campagne de vaccination de masse dans les zones affect\xe9es de Dono-Manga et Goundi, ainsi que 228 000 doses de vaccin bivalent pour une campagne \xe0 Doba et B\xe9bidja. Ces vaccins sont fournis avec l\u2019aide de l\u2019Alliance mondiale pour les vaccins et la vaccination (GAVI). Les campagnes de vaccination sont termin\xe9es ou sont en cours dans les districts de B\xe9bidja et Doba et elles auront prochainement lieu dans les districts de Dono-Manga et Goundi.  L\u2019OMS, l\u2019UNICEF, M\xe9decins Sans Fronti\xe8res et la F\xe9d\xe9ration internationale des Soci\xe9t\xe9s de la Croix-Rouge et du Croissant-Rouge collaborent avec le Minist\xe8re de la Sant\xe9 du Tchad \xe0 la mise en \u0153uvre des campagnes de vaccination ainsi que d\u2019autres mesures de lutte d\u2019urgence, dont la prise en charge des cas et la surveillance dans les districts voisins. ', 'Chad | Meningitis | Humans'

Meningococcal disease in Chad
u' Sesenta y siete muestras de l\xedquido cefalorraqu\xeddeo han sido positivas para Neisseria meningitidis del serogrupo A mediante la prueba del l\xe1tex, y 14 para N. meningitidis del serogrupo W135 mediante la prueba del l\xe1tex y el cultivo. Los resultados indican que algunas zonas est\xe1n sufriendo epidemias mixtas (distrito de Dono-Manga), mientras que otras se est\xe1n viendo afectadas predominantemente por el serogrupo A (distritos de Doba y, B\xe9bidja) o el serogrupo W135 (distrito de Goundi). El Grupo internacional coordinador del suministro de vacunas para controlar la meningitis epid\xe9mica ha aportado 157 000 dosis de vacuna trivalente ACW para una campa\xf1a de vacunaci\xf3n en masa en las zonas afectadas de Dono-Manga y Goundi, m\xe1s 282 000 dosis de vacuna bivalente para una campa\xf1a de vacunaci\xf3n en masa en Doba y B\xe9bidja. El suministro de las vacunas se est\xe1 haciendo con el apoyo de la Alianza GAVI. Las campa\xf1as est\xe1n en curso o ya han finalizado en los distritos de B\xe9bidja and Doba, mientras que en los de Dono-Manga y Goundi empezar\xe1n dentro de poco tiempo. La OMS, el UNICEF, M\xe9decins sans Fronti\xe8res y la Federaci\xf3n Internacional de Sociedades de la Cruz Roja y de la Media Luna Roja est\xe1n colaborando con el Ministerio de Salud del Chad para llevar a cabo las campa\xf1as de vacunaci\xf3n y otras medidas de control de emergencia, tales como el tratamiento de los casos y la vigilancia en los distritos vecinos. 405686

Google News
6 Apr 2010
C. difficile
Perth Royal Infirmary, Scotland, United Kingdom
'56.396339','-3.452950',5,11266
Top scientist calls for probe into fatal outbreak of C. diff - Press ...
u'A LEADING expert on hospital superbugs has called for an investigation into a fatal outbreak of Clostridium difficile in a Perthshire hospital.\n\nAberdeen-based bacteriologist Professor Hugh Pennington said an investigation was needed after an elderly patient died in Perth Royal Infirmary and three others tested positive for the bug.\n\nProf Pennington said the investigation should include a review of infection control procedures and was needed to reassure the public.\n\nIt is the second fatal outbreak of C. diff in the NHS Tayside health board area in the past six months.\n\nThe virus caused the death of two patients at Ninewells Hospital in Dundee and contributed to the deaths of three others in October last year.\n\nProf Pennington said: \xe2\x80\x9cThis is the second serious outbreak in one health board area so I am sure they will be reviewing their infection control procedures again and, one would hope, undertake an investigation.\n\n\xe2\x80\x9cHaving been through an unpleasant experience recently, the health board needs to show it has learned the lessons and implemented appropriate policies for dealing with it throughout the health board area.\n\n\xe2\x80\x9cWe don\xe2\x80\x99t know yet whether this is a hospital-spread outbreak or whether it was bought in by one of the patients. It is important to find that out and will help determine whether policy is being implemented effectively in Perth.\n\n\xe2\x80\x9cNHS Tayside was criticised last time for the length of time it took to release information and I would hope we get information about this outbreak sooner rather than later because the health board has got to reassure the public that effective control methods are in place.\xe2\x80\x9d\n\nAccording to NHS Tayside, the first patient tested positive for C. diff on February 12 and died in late March.\n\nThe other patients infected with the virus tested positive on March 30, April 2 and April 4 and resulted in the closure of the hospital\xe2\x80\x99s Tay ward to all new admissions.\n\nThe patients are currently being treated in isolation while a further 20 patients remain in the ward under observation.\n\nA spokeswoman for NHS Tayside said: \xe2\x80\x9cWe are closely monitoring the situation and there are no further updates.\xe2\x80\x9d\n\nThe Scottish Government was informed of the outbreak on Sunday.\n\nA spokeswoman said: \xe2\x80\x9cNHS Tayside have taken the steps necessary to contain the situation and we are being kept fully informed.\xe2\x80\x9d\n\n ', 'Perth Royal Infirmary, Scotland, United Kingdom | C. difficile | Humans'

Viral disease claims 200 sheep, goats
'KHARAN Apr 1 (PPI): A viral disease epidemic has claimed over 200 sheep and goats near here. The disease is so dangerous it was not being controlled by veterinary and Livestock department officials. According to details, a viral disease was rapidly spreading in Aabdari area some 45 Km northeast of Kharan. Sheep and goats suddenly fall on the ground and die. Veterinary experts and Livestock Department officials were providing vaccines to the animals but they were not proving useful as the disease is said to be very dangerous. They said vaccines form Quetta or Karachi should be provided so that animals could be vaccinated against the epidemic.  ', 'Pakistan | Other Animal Disease | Humans'

u' Uganda Health News: Strange disease hits Mityana \n First published: 20100402 5:13:05 AM EST \nUltimate Media Experts from the Ministry of Health in Kampala are in Mityana district to investigate a strange disease that has reportedly hit the area. The disease that is reported to have symptoms similar to that of Ebola broke out in Mityana north last week. Two people and seven children are reportedly ill suffering from vomiting and diarrhea. The Minister of State for Primary Health Care, James Kakooza says he cannot confirm whether the disease is Ebola until the health experts give the ministry of Health a report. '3.216260','73.252251',5,143
Chikungunya fever in two German tourists returning from the ...
'This report describes the first isolation and molecular characterisation of a chikungunya virus from two German tourists who became ill after a visit to the Maldives in September 2009. The virus contained the E1 A226V mutation, shown to be responsible for an adaptation to the Asian tiger mosquito Aedes albopictus. The E1 coding sequence was identical to chikungunya virus isolates from Sri Lanka and showed three nt-mismatches to the only available E1 nt sequence from the Maldives.  ', 'Maldives | Chikungunya | Humans'

Spotlight on measles 2010: Preliminary report of an ongoing measles...
'Since early January 2010, Berlin has been experiencing a measles outbreak with 62 cases as of 31 March. The index case acquired the infection in India. In recent years, measles incidence in Berlin has been lower than the German average and vaccination coverage in school children has increased since 2001. However, this outbreak involves schools and kindergartens with low vaccination coverage and parents with critical attitudes towards vaccination, which makes the implementation of public health interventions challenging. \n ', 'Berlin, Germany | Measles | Humans'

'15.361170','18.664480',5,57
Meningococcal disease in Chad
u' Sixty seven specimens of cerebral spinal fluid have been found positive for Neisseria meningitidis serogroup A by latex test while 14 specimens were found positive for Neisseria meningitidis serogroup W135, by latex, and culture. This indicates that some areas are experiencing mixed epidemics (Dono-Manga), while others are being predominantly affected by either serogroup A (Doba, B\xe9bidja district ) or serogroup W135 (Goundi district). The International Coordinating Group (ICG) on Vaccine Provision for Epidemic Meningitis Control has provided 157,000 doses of trivalent ACW vaccine for a mass vaccination campaign in affected areas of Dono-Manga and Goundi as well as 282,000 doses of bivalent vaccine for mass vaccination in Doba and Bebidja. Vaccines are being provided with the support of the Global Alliance for Vaccines and Immunization (GAVI). Vaccination campaigns have been completed or are being conducted in B\xe9bidja and Doba district, while others will take place shortly in Dono-Manga and Goundi districts. WHO, UNICEF, M\xe9decins sans Fronti\xe8res and the International Federation of Red Cross (IFRC) are working with the Ministry of Health, Chad to implement the vaccination campaigns as well as other emergency control measures, including case management and surveillance in neighbouring districts.  ', 'Chad | Bacterial Meningitis | Humans'
